frameDefinitions: A Person or Institution is being described in terms of their wealthiness, in other words the amount of money in their possession.
Despite some implication that a State would be interrupted, the Entity remains in the specified State.
This frame is for words that denote highly schematic entities.
A Payer gives up (or potentially gives up) the use of an Asset (generally money) in order to achieve an Intended_event.
An Owner has (or lacks) a Possession. ''
This frame has to do with nouns denoting types of entities.
frameExamples: We found an unusual wooden <t>object</t> in the desert.
It 'll <t>cost</t> Sandra's parents fifty grand a year for her to attend that school.
The river's part of my  manor, but of course it also <t>belongs</t> to the River Police.
I don't like this newfangled <t><fex name='Subtype'>kind</fex></t> of  fish.
listRoleDefinitions: The individual or individuals whose wealthiness is being described.
A group which has (or lacks) possession of some resource.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>State</fen> is found to still persist.
The location where the <fen>Entity</fen> is in the <fen>State</fen>.
A thing (either abstract or physical) that exists with some degree of permanence.
The role <fen>Goods</fen> is the item(s) whose price is being assessed.  <fen>Goods</fen> is usually an External Argument:
The person whose <fen>Asset</fen> is given up in order to achieve an <fen>Intended_event</fen>.  This role is often expressed as INI.
The price of or payment made for the Goods.
The event that the <fen>Payer</fen> brings about by deploying the <fen>Asset</fen>.
The time when a transaction takes place.
The entity that owns a posession.

The thing which is owned by the Owner.
Ex.:  I <t>have</t> <fex name='Possession'>twenty bucks</fex>.
(This does not include bodyparts or medical conditions, but does include intellectual property, etc.)
This role indicates the <fen>Time</fen> interval during which the <fen>Owner</fen> has a possession.
The entity which denotes a subtype of the more general <fen>Category</fen>.
The more general type that the target denotes a subtype of. This role is obligatory and should be labeled DNI when not present.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Pat and Kim</fex> are completely broke at the moment.

No, they've got a special on; it's really cheap there <fex>on Tuesdays</fex>
